		<div class="qna-section">
			<div class="question">Question  4:Now coming to the most dreaded part of every recruitment process, describe your interview(s)(include projects)</div>

			<div class="answer">Answer: 
			
			Interviews have always been a plus-point for me because I think I have an edge over others in terms of expressing myself and explaining my point to the interviewer.

			As robotics is a relatively new field so I gave 4 off-campus interviews out of which I had offers from 3 companies, and for on-campus I had offers from 2 companies(Infineon and Addverb) out of 2 companies for which I got a chance to interview for. So my interview to final job conversion rate was pretty high. 
			<ul style="margin-left:20px">
			<li>So for <b>Rightbot</b>, the questions were on:-
			<ul style="margin-left:20px"><li>
			<b>Programming:-</b> 
				<ol style="margin-left:20px">
				<li>Swapping of numbers.</li> 
				<li>Linked-List</li>
				<li>Oops</li>
				<li>File handling </li></ol>
			</li>
			<li><b>ROS:-</b>
				<ol style="margin-left:20px">
				<li> Communications in ROS</li>
				<li> Navigation_Stack. </li></ol>
			</li>
			<li>For all the robotics firms the questions basically revolved around coding, ROS and projects.</li></ul>

			<li>And for <b>Infineon</b>, all questions were on projects and only a handful on coding for the software role. In projects, I mentioned 3 projects all made in 3 different years (2nd, 3rd, 4th) basically to show my consistency. 

			So 2 projects were majorly asked one, on which I have a research paper published which is based on Stereo-Vision and another which used ROS for 2-D autonomous indoor navigation of a drone. </li>
			</ol>

			One important thing in the interview is to be totally honest with the interviewer and not guess answers to the questions you don't know no matter how frequent that has to happen. Sometimes they continuously ask tough questions to check how you handle situations which you don't have answers to. But at the same time, you have to be confident in your skill so that even if the question is not direct you can mould the answer according to your convenience. This balance is vital, according to me. 
			</div>
		</div>

